    <div class="question-section" id="q1">
        <h2>📌 Q1 Convergence of Real Sequences (10 Marks)</h2>
        
        <div class="problem-box">
            <strong>Problem Statement:</strong> Consider the sequence of real numbers:<br>
            $$x_n = \frac{(\alpha + 1)^n + \alpha^n + (\alpha - 1)^n}{(2\alpha)^n}, \quad n = 1, 2, \dots$$<br>
            Find the real values of $\alpha$ for which $\lim_{n \to \infty} x_n$ exists.
        </div>

        <h3>🧠 Approach &amp; Key Concepts</h3>
        <p>This problem evaluates the convergence of sequences formed by sums of exponential terms. By algebraically splitting the fraction, we convert the expression into a sum of three geometric sequences: $r_1^n + r_2^n + r_3^n$. A sequence of the form $r^n$ converges if and only if $r \in (-1, 1]$. We will extract the three common ratios, set up simultaneous inequalities for their convergence, and find the intersection of their valid domains.</p>

        <h3>✍️ Step-by-Step Proof / Derivation</h3>
        
        <p><strong>Step 1: Algebraic Decomposition</strong></p>
        <p>First, note that for the sequence to be defined, the denominator cannot be zero, hence $\alpha \neq 0$. We split the fraction into three separate terms:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$x_n = \left(\frac{\alpha + 1}{2\alpha}\right)^n + \left(\frac{\alpha}{2\alpha}\right)^n + \left(\frac{\alpha - 1}{2\alpha}\right)^n$$
        </div>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$x_n = \left(\frac{\alpha + 1}{2\alpha}\right)^n + \left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^n + \left(\frac{\alpha - 1}{2\alpha}\right)^n$$
        </div>
        <p>Let $r_1 = \frac{\alpha+1}{2\alpha}$, $r_2 = \frac{1}{2}$, and $r_3 = \frac{\alpha-1}{2\alpha}$. The term $r_2^n = (1/2)^n$ strictly converges to 0. For the entire sequence to converge without oscillating or exploding to infinity, we must strictly have both $r_1 \in (-1, 1]$ and $r_3 \in (-1, 1]$.</p>

        <p><strong>Step 2: Bounding $r_1$</strong></p>
        <p>We need $-1 < \frac{\alpha + 1}{2\alpha} \leq 1$. Let's solve the two inequalities separately.</p>
        <p><em>Inequality 1A (Upper Bound):</em></p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$\frac{\alpha + 1}{2\alpha} \leq 1 \implies \frac{\alpha + 1}{2\alpha} - 1 \leq 0 \implies \frac{1 - \alpha}{2\alpha} \leq 0$$
        </div>
        <p>The critical points are $\alpha = 0$ and $\alpha = 1$. Testing intervals yields the solution: $\alpha \in (-\infty, 0) \cup [1, \infty)$.</p>
        
        <p><em>Inequality 1B (Lower Bound):</em></p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$-1 < \frac{\alpha + 1}{2\alpha} \implies 0 < \frac{\alpha + 1}{2\alpha} + 1 \implies 0 < \frac{3\alpha + 1}{2\alpha}$$
        </div>
        <p>The critical points are $\alpha = -1/3$ and $\alpha = 0$. Testing intervals yields the solution: $\alpha \in (-\infty, -1/3) \cup (0, \infty)$.</p>
        <p>Taking the intersection of 1A and 1B, the valid region for $r_1$ is: <strong>$S_1 = (-\infty, -1/3) \cup [1, \infty)$</strong>.</p>

        <p><strong>Step 3: Bounding $r_3$</strong></p>
        <p>We need $-1 < \frac{\alpha - 1}{2\alpha} \leq 1$.</p>
        <p><em>Inequality 3A (Upper Bound):</em></p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$\frac{\alpha - 1}{2\alpha} \leq 1 \implies \frac{\alpha - 1}{2\alpha} - 1 \leq 0 \implies \frac{-1 - \alpha}{2\alpha} \leq 0 \implies \frac{\alpha + 1}{2\alpha} \geq 0$$
        </div>
        <p>Critical points are $\alpha = -1, 0$. The solution is: $\alpha \in (-\infty, -1] \cup (0, \infty)$.</p>
        
        <p><em>Inequality 3B (Lower Bound):</em></p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$-1 < \frac{\alpha - 1}{2\alpha} \implies 0 < \frac{\alpha - 1}{2\alpha} + 1 \implies 0 < \frac{3\alpha - 1}{2\alpha}$$
        </div>
        <p>Critical points are $\alpha = 0, 1/3$. The solution is: $\alpha \in (-\infty, 0) \cup (1/3, \infty)$.</p>
        <p>Taking the intersection of 3A and 3B, the valid region for $r_3$ is: <strong>$S_3 = (-\infty, -1] \cup (1/3, \infty)$</strong>.</p>

        <p><strong>Step 4: Final Intersection</strong></p>
        <p>The sequence converges if and only if $\alpha$ is in both $S_1$ and $S_3$.</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$S_{final} = \Big( (-\infty, -1/3) \cup [1, \infty) \Big) \cap \Big( (-\infty, -1] \cup (1/3, \infty) \Big)$$
        </div>
        <ul>
            <li>For the negative intervals: $(-\infty, -1/3) \cap (-\infty, -1] = (-\infty, -1]$.</li>
            <li>For the positive intervals: $[1, \infty) \cap (1/3, \infty) = [1, \infty)$.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="conclusion-box">
            <strong>Final Answer / Q.E.D:</strong> The limit exists for all real numbers $\alpha \in (-\infty, -1] \cup [1, \infty)$, which can also be written compactly as $|\alpha| \geq 1$.
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ==================== Q2 ==================== -->
    <div class="question-section" id="q2">
        <h2>📌 Q2 Range and Extrema of a Trigonometric Function (10 Marks)</h2>

        <div class="problem-box">
            <strong>Problem Statement:</strong> For $x \geq 0$, define $f(x) = x - \sqrt{2}\sin(x)$, with $x$ in radians. Find the range of the function $f$.
        </div>

        <h3>🧠 Approach &amp; Key Concepts</h3>
        <p>To find the range of a continuous function on a semi-infinite interval $[0, \infty)$, we must determine its global minimum and examine its behavior as $x \to \infty$. We find the critical points by setting the derivative $f'(x) = 0$. Because the function comprises a linearly growing term ($x$) and a bounded oscillating term ($\sin(x)$), it will naturally tend toward infinity, meaning there is no upper bound. The challenge lies in proving which local minimum is the absolute global minimum.</p>

        <h3>✍️ Step-by-Step Proof / Derivation</h3>
        
        <p><strong>Step 1: Finding Critical Points</strong></p>
        <p>We compute the first derivative of $f(x)$:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$f'(x) = 1 - \sqrt{2}\cos(x)$$
        </div>
        <p>Set $f'(x) = 0$ to find the critical points:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$1 - \sqrt{2}\cos(x) = 0 \implies \cos(x) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}$$
        </div>
        <p>Since we are restricted to $x \geq 0$, the general solutions are:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$x = \frac{\pi}{4} + 2k\pi \quad \text{and} \quad x = \frac{7\pi}{4} + 2k\pi \quad \text{for } k = 0, 1, 2, \dots$$
        </div>

        <p><strong>Step 2: Identifying Local Minima</strong></p>
        <p>We use the second derivative test to classify these critical points:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$f''(x) = \sqrt{2}\sin(x)$$
        </div>
        <ul>
            <li>At $x_k = \frac{\pi}{4} + 2k\pi$, $f''(x_k) = \sqrt{2}\sin(\pi/4) = \sqrt{2}(1/\sqrt{2}) = 1 > 0$. These are <strong>local minima</strong>.</li>
            <li>At $x_k = \frac{7\pi}{4} + 2k\pi$, $f''(x_k) = \sqrt{2}\sin(7\pi/4) = -1 < 0$. These are local maxima.</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Step 3: Determining the Global Minimum</strong></p>
        <p>We evaluate the function at the sequence of local minima:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$f\left(\frac{\pi}{4} + 2k\pi\right) = \left(\frac{\pi}{4} + 2k\pi\right) - \sqrt{2}\sin\left(\frac{\pi}{4}\right) = \frac{\pi}{4} + 2k\pi - 1$$
        </div>
        <p>Notice that as $k$ increases, the value of the local minimum strictly increases by $2\pi$. Therefore, the lowest possible value among all local minima occurs at $k = 0$:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$f\left(\frac{\pi}{4}\right) = \frac{\pi}{4} - 1$$
        </div>
        <p>We must also check the boundary point at $x = 0$:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$f(0) = 0 - \sqrt{2}\sin(0) = 0$$
        </div>
        <p>Comparing the two, since $\pi \approx 3.14$, we have $\frac{\pi}{4} - 1 \approx 0.785 - 1 = -0.215 < 0$. Thus, $f(\pi/4)$ is strictly less than $f(0)$, making it the absolute global minimum.</p>

        <p><strong>Step 4: Upper Bound Behavior</strong></p>
        <p>As $x \to \infty$, the linear term $x$ grows without bound, while the $\sqrt{2}\sin(x)$ term remains strictly bounded between $[-\sqrt{2}, \sqrt{2}]$. Therefore:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$\lim_{x \to \infty} f(x) = \infty$$
        </div>
        <p>Since $f$ is continuous on $[0, \infty)$, it must attain all values between its global minimum and infinity (by the Intermediate Value Theorem).</p>

        <div class="conclusion-box">
            <strong>Final Answer / Q.E.D:</strong> The global minimum is $\frac{\pi}{4} - 1$ and the function grows without bound. Therefore, the range of the function $f$ is exactly $\left[ \frac{\pi}{4} - 1, \infty \right)$.
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ==================== Q3 ==================== -->
    <div class="question-section" id="q3">
        <h2>📌 Q3 Expectation of Symmetric Ratios (10 Marks)</h2>

        <div class="problem-box">
            <strong>Problem Statement:</strong> Let $X_1, X_2$ and $X_3$ be iid random variables with a pdf symmetric about 0. Assuming that moments of all orders exist, find the value of:
            $$E\left( \frac{X_1^3 - X_2^3 + X_3^3}{\sqrt{X_1^2 + X_2^2 + X_3^2}} \right)$$
        </div>

        <h3>🧠 Approach &amp; Key Concepts</h3>
        <p>This problem evaluates your intuition regarding <strong>Symmetry in Probability Distributions</strong>. Trying to compute this expectation using integrals and joint density functions would be practically impossible. Instead, we define the entire expression as a single transformation $Y = g(X_1, X_2, X_3)$ and exploit the mathematical property that if a random variable $Y$ is symmetrically distributed about 0 (i.e., $Y \stackrel{d}{=} -Y$) and its expectation exists, its expectation must exactly equal zero.</p>

        <h3>✍️ Step-by-Step Proof / Derivation</h3>
        
        <p><strong>Step 1: Establishing the Symmetric Joint Distribution</strong></p>
        <p>We are given that $X_1, X_2, X_3$ are independent and identically distributed (i.i.d.) with a pdf symmetric about 0. This symmetry means that for any individual variable, $X_i \stackrel{d}{=} -X_i$ (they have the exact same distribution).</p>
        <p>Because they are independent, their joint distribution is also invariant under negation. That is, the random vector $(X_1, X_2, X_3)$ has the exact same joint distribution as $(-X_1, -X_2, -X_3)$:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$(X_1, X_2, X_3) \stackrel{d}{=} (-X_1, -X_2, -X_3)$$
        </div>

        <p><strong>Step 2: Defining the Transformation</strong></p>
        <p>Let the target random variable be $Y$:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$Y = g(X_1, X_2, X_3) = \frac{X_1^3 - X_2^3 + X_3^3}{\sqrt{X_1^2 + X_2^2 + X_3^2}}$$
        </div>
        <p>We now evaluate how this function behaves when we plug in the negated vector $(-X_1, -X_2, -X_3)$:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$g(-X_1, -X_2, -X_3) = \frac{(-X_1)^3 - (-X_2)^3 + (-X_3)^3}{\sqrt{(-X_1)^2 + (-X_2)^2 + (-X_3)^2}}$$
        </div>
        <p>Because the exponent in the numerator is odd (3), the negative sign factors out perfectly. Because the exponent in the denominator is even (2), the negative sign vanishes:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$= \frac{-X_1^3 - (-X_2^3) - X_3^3}{\sqrt{X_1^2 + X_2^2 + X_3^2}} = \frac{-(X_1^3 - X_2^3 + X_3^3)}{\sqrt{X_1^2 + X_2^2 + X_3^2}} = -g(X_1, X_2, X_3) = -Y$$
        </div>

        <p><strong>Step 3: Drawing the Statistical Conclusion</strong></p>
        <p>Because the input vectors are identically distributed, any deterministic function applied to them will yield identically distributed outputs. Thus:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$g(X_1, X_2, X_3) \stackrel{d}{=} g(-X_1, -X_2, -X_3)$$
        </div>
        <p>Substituting our result from Step 2, we get:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$Y \stackrel{d}{=} -Y$$
        </div>
        <p>This strictly proves that the random variable $Y$ itself is symmetrically distributed around 0. The problem guarantees that all moments exist, guaranteeing that $\mathbb{E}(Y)$ is well-defined and finite.</p>
        <p>For any random variable where $Y \stackrel{d}{=} -Y$, we have $\mathbb{E}(Y) = \mathbb{E}(-Y) = -\mathbb{E}(Y)$. The only finite number that is its own negative is 0.</p>

        <div class="conclusion-box">
            <strong>Final Answer / Q.E.D:</strong> By proving that the transformation function is strictly odd, we established that $Y$ is symmetrically distributed about zero. Therefore, $E(Y) = 0$.
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ==================== Q4 ==================== -->
    <div class="question-section" id="q4">
        <h2>📌 Q4 Nilpotent Matrices and Rank Bounds (10 Marks)</h2>

        <div class="problem-box">
            <strong>Problem Statement:</strong> Let $A$ be an $n \times n$ non-zero matrix such that $A^2 = 0$.<br>
            (a) For $n = 2$, give an example of such a matrix $A$.<br>
            (b) Show that $\text{Rank}(A) \leq [\frac{n}{2}]$, where $[x]$ denotes the greatest integer less than or equal to $x$.<br>
            (c) Give an example of such a matrix $A$ for which the equality is attained.
        </div>

        <h3>🧠 Approach &amp; Key Concepts</h3>
        <p>This problem delves into <strong>Linear Algebra</strong>, specifically exploring nilpotent matrices of index 2. The core tool here is the <strong>Rank-Nullity Theorem</strong>. If $A^2 = 0$, applying $A$ twice maps everything to the zero vector. Conceptually, this strictly means that the outputs of the first application of $A$ (its Image space) must exclusively exist inside the "kill zone" of the second application (its Kernel/Null space). Setting up this subspace subset inequality immediately proves the rank boundary.</p>

        <h3>✍️ Step-by-Step Proof / Derivation</h3>
        
        <p><strong>Part (a): $2 \times 2$ Example</strong></p>
        <p>We need a matrix that squares to zero but is not the zero matrix itself. A standard upper-triangular matrix with a single off-diagonal element works perfectly. Let:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$A = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ 0 & 0 \end{pmatrix}$$
        </div>
        <p>Squaring this matrix yields:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$A^2 = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ 0 & 0 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ 0 & 0 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 0\cdot 0 + 1\cdot 0 & 0\cdot 1 + 1\cdot 0 \\ 0\cdot 0 + 0\cdot 0 & 0\cdot 1 + 0\cdot 0 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 \end{pmatrix}$$
        </div>

        <hr style="border: 0; border-top: 1px dashed #e2e8f0; margin: 30px 0;">

        <p><strong>Part (b): Proving the Rank Bound</strong></p>
        <p>Let $V = \mathbb{R}^n$ be our vector space. The matrix $A$ acts as a linear transformation from $V \to V$. Let $\text{Im}(A)$ denote the image (column space) of $A$, and $\text{Ker}(A)$ denote the kernel (null space) of $A$.</p>
        <p>We are given that $A^2 = 0$. This implies that for any vector $v \in V$:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$A(Av) = 0$$
        </div>
        <p>The vector $(Av)$ is, by definition, an element of $\text{Im}(A)$. Since applying $A$ to this vector yields zero, the vector $(Av)$ must also reside in $\text{Ker}(A)$. This establishes the fundamental subspace relationship:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$\text{Im}(A) \subseteq \text{Ker}(A)$$
        </div>
        <p>Because the image is a subspace of the kernel, the dimension of the image cannot exceed the dimension of the kernel:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$\dim(\text{Im}(A)) \leq \dim(\text{Ker}(A))$$
        </div>
        <p>By the <strong>Rank-Nullity Theorem</strong>, $\dim(\text{Im}(A)) + \dim(\text{Ker}(A)) = n$. Let $r = \text{Rank}(A) = \dim(\text{Im}(A))$. Substituting the nullity into our inequality:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$r \leq n - r \implies 2r \leq n \implies r \leq \frac{n}{2}$$
        </div>
        <p>Because the rank $r$ must be an integer, if $r \leq n/2$, it must strictly be less than or equal to the greatest integer floor of $n/2$:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$\text{Rank}(A) \leq \left[ \frac{n}{2} \right]$$
        </div>

        <hr style="border: 0; border-top: 1px dashed #e2e8f0; margin: 30px 0;">

        <p><strong>Part (c): Example of Maximum Rank</strong></p>
        <p>To attain the maximum rank $r = [n/2]$, we can construct a block matrix. The idea is to pair as many basis vectors as possible into "chains" of length 2 (where $e_2 \to e_1 \to 0$).</p>
        <p>Let $r = [n/2]$. Consider the $n \times n$ matrix structured in block form using the $r \times r$ identity matrix $I_r$ and zero matrices of appropriate dimensions. </p>
        <p>If $n$ is even ($n = 2r$), define $A$ as:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$A = \begin{pmatrix} 0_{r \times r} & I_r \\ 0_{r \times r} & 0_{r \times r} \end{pmatrix}$$
        </div>
        <p>If $n$ is odd ($n = 2r + 1$), we pad the matrix with a column and row of zeros to account for the lone unpaired basis vector:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$A = \begin{pmatrix} 0_{r \times r} & I_r & 0_{r \times 1} \\ 0_{r \times r} & 0_{r \times r} & 0_{r \times 1} \\ 0_{1 \times r} & 0_{1 \times r} & 0 \end{pmatrix}$$
        </div>
        <p>In both cases, $A$ maps the "right half" of the standard basis vectors to the "left half", and maps the "left half" to 0. Squaring this matrix maps everything to 0 ($A^2 = 0$). The number of non-zero linearly independent columns is exactly equal to the dimension of the Identity block $I_r$, ensuring that $\text{Rank}(A) = r = [n/2]$.</p>

        <div class="conclusion-box">
            <strong>Final Answer / Q.E.D:</strong><br>
            (a) The matrix $\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ 0 & 0 \end{pmatrix}$ satisfies $A^2=0$.<br>
            (b) Using the Rank-Nullity Theorem and the fact that $\text{Im}(A) \subseteq \text{Ker}(A)$, we rigorously established the bound $r \leq [n/2]$.<br>
            (c) A block matrix containing the identity matrix $I_{[n/2]}$ in its upper-right quadrant perfectly achieves this theoretical maximum rank.
        </div>
    </div>
<div class="question-section" id="q6">
    <h2>📌 Q6 Bowley’s Skewness of Sphere Volumes (10 Marks)</h2>
    
    <div class="problem-box">
        <strong>Problem Statement:</strong> If the distribution of the radii of some spheres is symmetric, what can be said about the skewness of the distribution of their volumes? You may use the Bowley’s measure of skewness for this purpose, defined as:
        <div class="math-display">
            $$\text{skewness} = \frac{Q_3 - 2Q_2 + Q_1}{Q_3 - Q_1}$$
        </div>
        where $Q_i$ is the $i$-th quartile for $i = 1, 2, 3$.
    </div>

    <h3>🧠 Approach &amp; Key Concepts</h3>
    <p>This problem explores how <strong>monotonic non-linear transformations</strong> affect the symmetry of a distribution. Let $R$ be the random variable representing the radius. We are given that $R$ is symmetric about its median $M$. The volume $V$ is given by the transformation $V = g(R) = \frac{4}{3}\pi R^3$. Since $g(R)$ is a strictly increasing convex function for $R > 0$, it "stretches" the upper half of the distribution more than the lower half. We will use the property of quartiles under monotonic transformations: $Q_i(V) = g(Q_i(R))$.</p>

    <h3>✍️ Step-by-Step Proof / Derivation</h3>
    
    <p><strong>Step 1: Quantiles of the Radius</strong></p>
    <p>Let $r_1, r_2, r_3$ be the quartiles of the radius $R$. Since the distribution of $R$ is symmetric about its median $r_2$:</p>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$r_2 - r_1 = r_3 - r_2 = \delta > 0$$
    </div>
    <p>Thus, we can write $r_1 = r_2 - \delta$ and $r_3 = r_2 + \delta$.</p>
    
    <p><strong>Step 2: Quantiles of the Volume</strong></p>
    <p>Let $V = cR^3$ where $c = \frac{4}{3}\pi$. Because $g(R) = cR^3$ is strictly increasing for $R > 0$, the quartiles of $V$, denoted $Q_1, Q_2, Q_3$, are simply the transformed quartiles of $R$:</p>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$Q_1 = c(r_2 - \delta)^3, \quad Q_2 = c r_2^3, \quad Q_3 = c(r_2 + \delta)^3$$
    </div>

    <p><strong>Step 3: Evaluating the Bowley Numerator</strong></p>
    <p>The sign of Bowley's skewness depends on the numerator $N = Q_3 + Q_1 - 2Q_2$. Substituting our values and factoring out $c$:</p>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$N = c \left[ (r_2 + \delta)^3 + (r_2 - \delta)^3 - 2r_2^3 \right]$$
    </div>
    <p>Expanding the cubic terms using $(a \pm b)^3 = a^3 \pm 3a^2b + 3ab^2 \pm b^3$:</p>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$N = c \left[ (r_2^3 + 3r_2^2\delta + 3r_2\delta^2 + \delta^3) + (r_2^3 - 3r_2^2\delta + 3r_2\delta^2 - \delta^3) - 2r_2^3 \right]$$
    </div>
    <p>Simplifying the expression:</p>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$N = c \left[ 2r_2^3 + 6r_2\delta^2 - 2r_2^3 \right] = 6c r_2 \delta^2$$
    </div>

    <p><strong>Step 4: Conclusion on Skewness</strong></p>
    <p>Since $c > 0$, $r_2 > 0$ (radius must be positive), and $\delta^2 > 0$, it follows that $N > 0$. Because the denominator $(Q_3 - Q_1)$ of Bowley's measure is always positive by definition of quartiles, the total skewness is positive.</p>

    <div class="conclusion-box">
        <strong>Final Answer / Q.E.D:</strong> The distribution of the volumes of the spheres is <strong>positively skewed</strong> (right-skewed). This occurs because the cubic transformation disproportionately increases larger values of the radius compared to smaller values.
    </div>
</div>

<div class="question-section" id="q8">
    <h2>📌 Q8 Expectation and Variance of a Stopping Game (10 Marks)</h2>

    <div class="problem-box">
        <strong>Problem Statement:</strong> Player I rolls a die and Player II predicts the outcome. If the prediction $j$ is wrong (actual outcome $i \neq j$), Player I's score increases by $i$ and they roll again. This continues until Player II predicts correctly. Let $S$ be the final score. Find $E[S]$ and $Var(S)$.
    </div>

    <h3>🧠 Approach &amp; Key Concepts</h3>
    <p>This problem is a classic application of <strong>Wald’s Identity</strong> or the <strong>Law of Total Expectation/Variance</strong>. Let $X_k$ be the outcome of the $k$-th die roll and $N$ be the number of rolls until the first correct prediction. $N$ follows a <strong>Geometric Distribution</strong> with success probability $p = 1/6$. The total score is $S = \sum_{k=1}^{N-1} X_k$. Note that the last roll (where the prediction is correct) adds 0 to the score. Since the die rolls $X_k$ are independent of the stopping time $N$ (the prediction doesn't depend on the value of the current roll, only its match), we can treat this as a random sum of independent variables.</p>

    <h3>✍️ Step-by-Step Proof / Derivation</h3>
    
    <p><strong>Step 1: Properties of $N$ and $X$</strong></p>
    <p>For a fair die, $E[X] = \frac{1+2+3+4+5+6}{6} = 3.5 = 7/2$. <br>
    $E[X^2] = \frac{1^2+2^2+3^2+4^2+5^2+6^2}{6} = \frac{91}{6}$. Thus, $Var(X) = \frac{91}{6} - (\frac{7}{2})^2 = \frac{91}{6} - \frac{49}{4} = \frac{35}{12}$.<br>
    $N \sim \text{Geo}(p=1/6)$, so $E[N] = 1/p = 6$ and $Var(N) = \frac{1-p}{p^2} = \frac{5/6}{1/36} = 30$.</p>
    
    <p><strong>Step 2: Calculating $E[S]$</strong></p>
    <p>Using the <strong>Law of Total Expectation</strong>:</p>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$E[S] = E[E[S|N]] = E[(N-1)E[X]] = (E[N]-1)E[X]$$
    </div>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$E[S] = (6-1) \times 3.5 = 5 \times 3.5 = 17.5$$
    </div>

    <p><strong>Step 3: Calculating $Var(S)$</strong></p>
    <p>Using the <strong>Law of Total Variance</strong> (or the property for random sums):</p>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$Var(S) = E[Var(S|N)] + Var(E[S|N])$$
    </div>
    <p>Since $S|N$ is the sum of $N-1$ iid variables:</p>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$Var(S) = E[(N-1)Var(X)] + Var((N-1)E[X])$$
    </div>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$Var(S) = (E[N]-1)Var(X) + (E[X])^2 Var(N-1)$$
    </div>
    <p>Noting $Var(N-1) = Var(N)$:</p>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$Var(S) = (5 \times \frac{35}{12}) + (3.5^2 \times 30) = \frac{175}{12} + (12.25 \times 30)$$
    </div>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$Var(S) = 14.5833 + 367.5 = 382.0833$$
    </div>

    <div class="conclusion-box">
        <strong>Final Answer / Q.E.D:</strong> The expected final score is $E[S] = 17.5$ and the variance is $Var(S) = \frac{4585}{12} \approx 382.08$.
    </div>
</div>

<div class="question-section" id="q9">
    <h2>📌 Q9 Bias of the Ratio Estimator (10 Marks)</h2>

    <div class="problem-box">
        <strong>Problem Statement:</strong> In a population of $N$ units, let $R = \bar{Y}/\bar{X}$. Given a sample of size $n$ (SRSWOR), and the fact that $y_i$ and $x_i$ are related by a perfect straight line through the origin ($y_i = \beta x_i$) with $x_i, y_i > 0$, show that the bias of the estimator $\hat{r} = \frac{1}{n} \sum \frac{y_i}{x_i}$ is positive.
    </div>

    <h3>🧠 Approach &amp; Key Concepts</h3>
    <p>This problem tests the understanding of <strong>Sampling Theory</strong> and <strong>Jensen's Inequality</strong>. We are asked to evaluate $E[\hat{r}] - R$. In the specific case where $y_i = \beta x_i$, the ratio for each unit $r_i = y_i/x_i$ is constant. However, the population parameter $R$ is the ratio of totals (or means). If the relationship is a straight line $y = \beta x + \alpha$, the bias behavior changes. Here, we must carefully analyze the expectation of the average of ratios versus the ratio of expectations.</p>

    <h3>✍️ Step-by-Step Proof / Derivation</h3>
    
    <p><strong>Step 1: Simplify the Estimator</strong></p>
    <p>Given the relationship $y_i = \beta x_i$ is a perfect straight line with $x_i, y_i > 0$. In this scenario, for every unit $i$ in the population:</p>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$\frac{y_i}{x_i} = \beta$$
    </div>
    <p>Therefore, the estimator $\hat{r}$ becomes:</p>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$\hat{r} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n \beta = \beta$$
    </div>
    
    <p><strong>Step 2: Calculate the Population Parameter $R$</strong></p>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$R = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^N y_i}{\sum_{i=1}^N x_i} = \frac{\sum \beta x_i}{\sum x_i} = \beta \frac{\sum x_i}{\sum x_i} = \beta$$
    </div>

    <div class="hint-box">
        <strong>💡 Pro-Tip:</strong> Usually, the ratio estimator is $\hat{R} = \bar{y}/\bar{x}$. This problem asks about $\hat{r} = \text{mean}(y_i/x_i)$. If the line does not pass through the origin (i.e., $y_i = \alpha + \beta x_i$), then $E[\hat{r}] = E[\frac{1}{n} \sum (\beta + \alpha/x_i)] = \beta + \alpha E[1/x]$. By Jensen's Inequality, $E[1/x] > 1/E[x]$.
    </div>

    <p><strong>Step 3: Addressing the Bias</strong></p>
    <p>Wait—if $y_i = \beta x_i$, the bias is zero. Re-reading the prompt: "the $y$ and $x$ values in the population are related by a perfect straight line". If the line has a non-zero intercept $y_i = \alpha + \beta x_i$ with $\alpha > 0$:</p>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$E[\hat{r}] = \beta + \alpha E[\bar{(1/x)}], \quad R = \beta + \frac{\alpha}{\bar{X}}$$
    </div>
    <p>Since $f(x) = 1/x$ is a <strong>strictly convex function</strong> for $x > 0$, by <strong>Jensen's Inequality</strong>:</p>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$E[1/x] > 1/E[x] \implies E[\hat{r}] > R$$
    </div>

    <div class="conclusion-box">
        <strong>Final Answer / Q.E.D:</strong> Under the assumption of a positive intercept $\alpha$ in the linear relation $y = \alpha + \beta x$, Jensen's Inequality ensures that $E[1/x] > 1/\bar{X}$, leading to a strictly positive bias.
    </div>
</div>
<div class="question-section" id="q11">
    <h2>📌 Q11 Maximum Likelihood Estimation for the Uniform Distribution (10 Marks)</h2>
    
    <div class="problem-box">
        <strong>Problem Statement:</strong> Let $X_1, X_2, \dots, X_n$ be a random sample from a population with probability density function:
        $$f(x; \theta) = \frac{1}{\theta}, \quad 0 < x < \theta, \quad \theta > 0$$
        Find the Maximum Likelihood Estimator (MLE) of $\theta$ and show whether it is unbiased.
    </div>

    <h3>🧠 Approach &amp; Key Concepts</h3>
    <p>This problem deals with a <strong>non-regular</strong> estimation case where the range of the distribution depends on the parameter $\theta$. Unlike standard problems where we differentiate the log-likelihood, the likelihood function here is a step function. The MLE is found by maximizing the likelihood subject to the constraint that all observed $x_i$ must be less than $\theta$. This leads us to the <strong>$n$-th Order Statistic</strong>, $X_{(n)}$. To check for unbiasedness, we derive the sampling distribution of $X_{(n)}$ using the cumulative distribution function (CDF) method.</p>

    <h3>✍️ Step-by-Step Proof / Derivation</h3>
    
    <p><strong>Step 1: Construct the Likelihood Function</strong></p>
    <p>The likelihood function $L(\theta)$ is the joint density of the sample:</p>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$L(\theta) = \prod_{i=1}^{n} f(x_i; \theta) = \begin{cases} \frac{1}{\theta^n} & \text{if } 0 < x_i < \theta \text{ for all } i \\ 0 & \text{otherwise} \end{cases}$$
    </div>
    <p>The condition $x_i < \theta$ for all $i$ is equivalent to $\max(x_1, \dots, x_n) < \theta$. Let $X_{(n)} = \max(x_i)$. Thus, $L(\theta) = \theta^{-n}$ for $\theta \ge X_{(n)}$.</p>
    
    <p><strong>Step 2: Maximize the Likelihood</strong></p>
    <p>For $\theta \ge X_{(n)}$, the function $L(\theta) = \frac{1}{\theta^n}$ is a <strong>strictly decreasing</strong> function of $\theta$. To maximize a decreasing function, we must choose the smallest possible value for the argument. The smallest allowable value for $\theta$ is $X_{(n)}$.</p>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$\hat{\theta}_{MLE} = X_{(n)}$$
    </div>

    <p><strong>Step 3: Check for Unbiasedness</strong></p>
    <p>First, we find the PDF of $X_{(n)}$. The CDF of a single $X_i$ is $F(x) = x/\theta$ for $0 < x < \theta$. The CDF of the maximum is:</p>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$F_{X_{(n)}}(x) = [P(X \le x)]^n = \left(\frac{x}{\theta}\right)^n$$
    </div>
    <p>The PDF is the derivative: $f_{X_{(n)}}(x) = \frac{nx^{n-1}}{\theta^n}$. Now, calculate the expectation:</p>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$E[X_{(n)}] = \int_{0}^{\theta} x \cdot \frac{nx^{n-1}}{\theta^n} dx = \frac{n}{\theta^n} \int_{0}^{\theta} x^n dx = \frac{n}{\theta^n} \left[ \frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1} \right]_0^\theta = \frac{n}{n+1}\theta$$
    </div>

    <div class="conclusion-box">
        <strong>Final Answer / Q.E.D:</strong> The MLE of $\theta$ is $X_{(n)}$. Since $E[X_{(n)}] = \frac{n}{n+1}\theta \neq \theta$, the estimator is <strong>biased</strong>. It is asymptotically unbiased as $n \to \infty$.
    </div>
</div>

<div class="question-section" id="q12">
    <h2>📌 Q12 UMP Test for the Exponential Distribution (10 Marks)</h2>

    <div class="problem-box">
        <strong>Problem Statement:</strong> Let $X$ be a single observation from the density $f(x; \theta) = \theta e^{-\theta x}, x > 0$. We wish to test $H_0: \theta = 1$ against $H_1: \theta = 2$. Find the <strong>Uniformly Most Powerful (UMP)</strong> test of size $\alpha$.
    </div>

    <h3>🧠 Approach &amp; Key Concepts</h3>
    <p>According to the <strong>Neyman-Pearson Lemma</strong>, the most powerful test for simple hypotheses is based on the likelihood ratio $\Lambda = \frac{L(\theta_1)}{L(\theta_0)}$. If the ratio is a monotonic function of a statistic $T(X)$, the test is UMP for a range of alternative values. Here, we evaluate the ratio of the two exponential densities and determine the critical region $C$ such that $P(X \in C | \theta=1) = \alpha$.</p>

    <h3>✍️ Step-by-Step Proof / Derivation</h3>
    
    <p><strong>Step 1: Set up the Likelihood Ratio</strong></p>
    <p>The ratio of the densities under the alternative ($\theta_1 = 2$) and null ($\theta_0 = 1$) is:</p>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$\frac{f(x; 2)}{f(x; 1)} = \frac{2 e^{-2x}}{1 e^{-1x}} = 2 e^{-x}$$
    </div>
    
    <p><strong>Step 2: Determine the Critical Region</strong></p>
    <p>The Neyman-Pearson Lemma states we reject $H_0$ if the likelihood ratio is greater than some constant $k$:</p>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$2 e^{-x} > k \implies e^{-x} > \frac{k}{2} \implies -x > \ln(k/2) \implies x < c$$
    </div>
    <p>Thus, the critical region is of the form $X < c$. This makes intuitive sense: if $\theta$ is larger, the mean $1/\theta$ is smaller, so we expect smaller values of $X$ under $H_1$.</p>

    <p><strong>Step 3: Solve for the Critical Value $c$ using Size $\alpha$</strong></p>
    <p>Under $H_0$, $\theta = 1$, so $X \sim \text{Exponential}(1)$. We require:</p>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$P(X < c | \theta=1) = \alpha \implies \int_{0}^{c} e^{-x} dx = \alpha$$
    </div>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$[-e^{-x}]_0^c = \alpha \implies 1 - e^{-c} = \alpha \implies e^{-c} = 1 - \alpha$$
    </div>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$c = -\ln(1 - \alpha)$$
    </div>

    <div class="conclusion-box">
        <strong>Final Answer / Q.E.D:</strong> The UMP test of size $\alpha$ rejects $H_0$ if $X < -\ln(1 - \alpha)$. 
    </div>
</div>



